nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Petit was born in 1226, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Le Petit, was 41 and his mother, Alice Seneschall, was 36. He married Alice Beauchamp in 1249, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1284, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1226–1284":"1226–1284","1227–1284":"1227–1284","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1255–1302":"1255–1302","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1252":"1252","10 JUN 1255":"10. juuni 1255","1284":"1284","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1249":"1249","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1225":"1225","1302":"1302","1255":"1255","Ardevora-Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cleev, Cornwall, England":"